1
00:00:41,638 --> 00:00:43,223
<i>For more than a year,</i>

2
00:00:43,307 --> 00:00:48,020
<i>ominous rumors had been privately circulating
among high-level Western leaders</i>

3
00:00:48,103 --> 00:00:50,063
<i>that the Soviet Union
had been at work</i>

4
00:00:50,147 --> 00:00:53,567
<i>on what was darkly hinted
to be the ultimate weapon,</i>

5
00:00:53,650 --> 00:00:55,736
<i>a doomsday device.</i>

6
00:00:55,819 --> 00:00:59,740
<i>Intelligence sources traced the site
of the top-secret Russian project</i>

7
00:00:59,823 --> 00:01:02,409
<i>to the perpetually
fog-shrouded wasteland</i>

8
00:01:02,493 --> 00:01:05,871
<i>below the Arctic peaks
of the Zhokhov Islands.</i>

9
00:01:05,954 --> 00:01:07,372
<i>What they were building,</i>

10
00:01:07,456 --> 00:01:11,335
<i>or why it should be located
in such a remote and desolate place,</i>

11
00:01:11,418 --> 00:01:13,420
<i>no one could say.</i>

12
00:03:43,779 --> 00:03:45,781
General Ripper, sir.

13
00:03:45,864 --> 00:03:47,574
Group Captain Mandrake speaking.

14
00:03:47,658 --> 00:03:50,619
- This is General Ripper speaking.
- Yes, sir.

15
00:03:50,702 --> 00:03:52,746
Do you recognize my voice, Mandrake?

16
00:03:52,829 --> 00:03:54,414
I do, sir. Why do you ask?

17
00:03:54,498 --> 00:03:56,250
Why do you think I ask?

18
00:03:56,333 --> 00:03:59,920
Well, I don't know, sir. We spoke just
a few moments ago on the phone, didn't we?

19
00:04:00,003 --> 00:04:02,381
You don't think I'd ask
if you recognized my voice

20
00:04:02,464 --> 00:04:05,175
unless it was pretty damned important,
do you, Mandrake?

21
00:04:05,259 --> 00:04:09,012
- No, I don't, sir, no.
- All right, let's see if we can stay on the ball.

22
00:04:09,930 --> 00:04:12,474
Has the wing confirmed
holding at their fail-safe points?

23
00:04:12,557 --> 00:04:15,435
Yes, sir, the confirmations
have all just come in.

24
00:04:15,519 --> 00:04:18,188
Very well. Now listen to me carefully.

25
00:04:19,189 --> 00:04:21,775
The base is being put on condition red.

26
00:04:21,858 --> 00:04:24,278
I want this flashed
to all sections immediately.

27
00:04:24,361 --> 00:04:27,656
Condition red, sir, yes. Jolly good idea.
Keeps the men on their toes.

28
00:04:27,739 --> 00:04:30,033
Group Captain,
I'm afraid this is not an exercise.

29
00:04:31,201 --> 00:04:32,995
Not an exercise, sir?

30
00:04:34,496 --> 00:04:36,123
I shouldn't tell you this, Mandrake,

31
00:04:36,206 --> 00:04:39,251
but you're a good officer
and you have a right to know.

32
00:04:39,334 --> 00:04:41,336
It looks like we're in a shooting war.

33
00:04:42,254 --> 00:04:43,630
Oh, hell.

34
00:04:44,381 --> 00:04:47,301
- Are the Russians involved, sir?
- Mandrake, that's all I've been told.

35
00:04:47,384 --> 00:04:48,969
It just came in on the red phone.

36
00:04:49,052 --> 00:04:53,140
My orders are for this base to be sealed tight,
and that's what I mean to do, seal it tight.

37
00:04:53,223 --> 00:04:56,643
Now, I want you to transmit plan "R",

38
00:04:56,727 --> 00:04:58,729
"R" for Robert, to the wing.

39
00:04:58,812 --> 00:05:00,647
plan "R" for Robert.

40
00:05:00,731 --> 00:05:02,190
Is it that bad, sir?

41
00:05:02,274 --> 00:05:04,818
- It looks like it's pretty hairy.
- Yes, sir.

42
00:05:04,901 --> 00:05:06,862
plan "R" for Robert, sir.

43
00:05:06,945 --> 00:05:10,157
Now last, and possibly most important,

44
00:05:10,240 --> 00:05:13,410
I want all privately owned radios
to be immediately impounded.

45
00:05:13,493 --> 00:05:14,911
Yes, sir.

46
00:05:14,995 --> 00:05:18,373
They might be used
to issue instructions to saboteurs.

47
00:05:18,457 --> 00:05:21,460
As I previously arranged,
air police will have lists of all owners,

48
00:05:21,543 --> 00:05:24,379
and I want every single one of them
collected without exception.

49
00:05:24,463 --> 00:05:25,797
Yes, sir.

50
00:05:25,881 --> 00:05:28,008
And after you've done that,
report back to me.

51
00:05:28,091 --> 00:05:29,551
Yes, sir.

52
00:05:54,910 --> 00:05:57,746
<i>In order to guard
against surprise nuclear attack,</i>

53
00:05:57,829 --> 00:06:03,043
<i>America's Strategic Air Command
maintains a large force of B-52 bombers,</i>

54
00:06:03,126 --> 00:06:05,462
<i>airborne 24 hours a day.</i>

55
00:06:06,046 --> 00:06:10,467
<i>Each B-52 can deliver
a nuclear bomb load of 50 megatons,</i>

56
00:06:11,093 --> 00:06:14,221
<i>equal to 16 times
the total explosive force</i>

57
00:06:14,304 --> 00:06:16,348
<i>of all the bombs and shells</i>

58
00:06:16,431 --> 00:06:20,060
<i>used by all the armies
in World War II.</i>

59
00:06:20,143 --> 00:06:22,646
<i>Based in America,
the Airborne Alert Force</i>

60
00:06:22,729 --> 00:06:26,108
<i>is deployed from the Persian Gulf
to the Arctic Ocean,</i>

61
00:06:26,191 --> 00:06:29,111
<i>but they have
one geographical factor in common.</i>

62
00:06:29,194 --> 00:06:33,156
<i>They are all two hours
from their targets inside Russia.</i>

63
00:07:52,986 --> 00:07:56,031
Major Kong,
I know you'll think this is crazy,

64
00:07:56,114 --> 00:07:59,743
but I just got a message from base
over the CRM 114,

65
00:08:00,785 --> 00:08:02,579
and it decodes
as Wing Attack plan "R",

66
00:08:03,455 --> 00:08:05,123
"R" for Romeo.

67
00:08:08,001 --> 00:08:12,339
Goldie, did you say
Wing Attack plan "R"?

68
00:08:12,422 --> 00:08:13,924
Yes, sir, I have.

69
00:08:17,594 --> 00:08:20,805
Goldie, how many times
have I told you guys

70
00:08:20,889 --> 00:08:24,100
that I don't want no horsing around
on the airplane?

71
00:08:24,184 --> 00:08:26,770
I'm not horsin' around, sir.
That's how it decodes.

72
00:08:26,853 --> 00:08:30,106
Well, I've been to one world fair,
a picnic and a rodeo,

73
00:08:30,190 --> 00:08:33,443
and that's the stupidest thing
I ever heard come over a set of earphones.

74
00:08:33,527 --> 00:08:35,445
You sure you got today's code?

75
00:08:37,072 --> 00:08:40,325
- Yes, sir, it is.
- There's just gotta be somethin' wrong.

76
00:08:40,408 --> 00:08:42,118
Wait a second. I'm coming back.

77
00:09:17,320 --> 00:09:20,991
Maybe you'd better
get a confirmation from base.

78
00:09:21,074 --> 00:09:22,659
Yes, sir.

79
00:09:43,513 --> 00:09:46,433
Major Kong, is it possible
this is some kind of loyalty test?

80
00:09:46,516 --> 00:09:50,186
You know, give the go code and then
recall to see who would actually go?

81
00:09:50,854 --> 00:09:53,648
Ain't nobody
ever got the go code yet.

82
00:09:54,441 --> 00:09:56,818
And old Ripper
wouldn't be giving us plan "R"

83
00:09:56,901 --> 00:09:59,279
unless them Russkies
had already clobbered Washington

84
00:09:59,362 --> 00:10:01,948
and a lot of other towns
with a sneak attack.

85
00:10:02,032 --> 00:10:03,199
Yes, sir.

86
00:10:03,283 --> 00:10:05,827
Major Kong,
message from base confirmed.

87
00:10:10,540 --> 00:10:12,959
Well, boys, I reckon this is it.

88
00:10:13,960 --> 00:10:17,047
Nuclear combat
toe to toe with the Russkies.

89
00:10:32,395 --> 00:10:37,233
Now, look, boys, I ain't much
of a hand at making speeches,

90
00:10:38,443 --> 00:10:40,111
but I got a pretty fair idea

91
00:10:40,195 --> 00:10:43,865
that something doggone important's
going on back there.

92
00:10:43,948 --> 00:10:47,494
Now, I got a fair idea
of the kind of personal emotions

93
00:10:47,577 --> 00:10:51,331
that some of you fellows may be thinkin'.

94
00:10:51,414 --> 00:10:54,334
Heck, I reckon you wouldn't even
be human beings

95
00:10:54,417 --> 00:10:59,005
if you didn't have some pretty strong
personal feelings about nuclear combat.

96
00:10:59,089 --> 00:11:01,675
But I want you to remember one thing

97
00:11:01,758 --> 00:11:04,386
that folks back home
is a-countin' on ya,

98
00:11:04,469 --> 00:11:07,263
and by golly,
we ain't about to let 'em down.

99
00:11:08,473 --> 00:11:10,058
Tell you something else.

100
00:11:11,518 --> 00:11:16,356
If this thing turns out to be half as
important as I figure it just might be,

101
00:11:16,439 --> 00:11:20,360
I'd say that you're all in line
for some important promotions

102
00:11:20,443 --> 00:11:24,197
and personal citations
when this thing's over with.

103
00:11:24,280 --> 00:11:27,117
And that goes for ever' last one of you,

104
00:11:27,200 --> 00:11:30,870
regardless of your race, color
or your creed.

105
00:11:30,954 --> 00:11:34,791
Now, let's get this thing on the hump.
We got some flyin' to do.

106
00:11:48,304 --> 00:11:50,557
Buck, should I get it?

107
00:11:50,640 --> 00:11:52,350
Yeah, you'll have to.

108
00:11:58,440 --> 00:12:00,233
Hello?

109
00:12:00,316 --> 00:12:01,860
Oh, yes, General Turgidson is here,

110
00:12:01,943 --> 00:12:04,946
but I'm afraid he can't come
to the phone at the moment.

111
00:12:05,029 --> 00:12:07,240
Well, this is his secretary, Miss Scott.

112
00:12:08,324 --> 00:12:10,368
Freddie, how are you?

113
00:12:10,452 --> 00:12:12,078
Fine. And you?

114
00:12:12,996 --> 00:12:16,291
Oh, we were just catching up
on some of the general's paperwork.

115
00:12:17,751 --> 00:12:20,503
Well, look, Freddie,
he's very tied up at the moment.

116
00:12:20,587 --> 00:12:23,423
I'm afraid he can't come to the phone.

117
00:12:23,506 --> 00:12:24,883
Oh, just a minute.

118
00:12:24,966 --> 00:12:28,261
General Turgidson.
A Colonel Puntrich calling.

119
00:12:28,344 --> 00:12:30,096
Tell him to call back.

120
00:12:30,180 --> 00:12:33,600
Freddie, the general says
could you call back in a minute or two?

121
00:12:34,559 --> 00:12:36,853
He says it can't wait.

122
00:12:36,936 --> 00:12:40,356
Aw, for Pete...
Well, find out what he wants.

123
00:12:40,440 --> 00:12:44,277
Freddie, the thing is, the general
is in the powder room right now.

124
00:12:44,360 --> 00:12:46,571
Could you tell me what it's about?

125
00:12:47,947 --> 00:12:49,365
Just a second.

126
00:12:49,449 --> 00:12:52,285
Apparently they monitored a transmission
about eight minutes ago

127
00:12:52,368 --> 00:12:54,662
from Burpelson Air Force Base.

128
00:12:56,247 --> 00:12:57,665
Got it.

129
00:12:57,749 --> 00:13:01,544
It was directed to the 843rd Bomb Wing
on airborne alert.

130
00:13:02,879 --> 00:13:06,966
It decoded as Wing Attack plan "R".

131
00:13:07,050 --> 00:13:11,262
Well, uh, tell him
to call, uh, what's-his-name,

132
00:13:11,346 --> 00:13:14,265
Base Commander Ripper.
Do I have to think of everything?

133
00:13:14,349 --> 00:13:16,601
The general suggests
you call General Ripper,

134
00:13:16,684 --> 00:13:19,145
the 843rd base commander.

135
00:13:19,229 --> 00:13:22,482
All communications are dead.

136
00:13:22,565 --> 00:13:25,276
Bull! Tell him to do it himself.

137
00:13:26,069 --> 00:13:29,572
Freddie, the general asks
if you could possibly try again yourself.

138
00:13:31,032 --> 00:13:32,158
I see.

139
00:13:32,242 --> 00:13:35,787
He says he's tried personally
several times, but everything is dead.

140
00:13:35,870 --> 00:13:38,581
Even the normal phone lines
are shut down.

141
00:13:43,753 --> 00:13:45,672
Give me that.

142
00:13:45,755 --> 00:13:47,549
Fred? Buck.

143
00:13:47,632 --> 00:13:49,175
What's it look like?

144
00:13:50,176 --> 00:13:51,761
Yeah?

145
00:13:53,137 --> 00:13:55,682
Well, are you sure it's plan "R"?

146
00:13:57,592 --> 00:14:00,186
What's cooking
on the threat board?

147
00:14:00,270 --> 00:14:02,605
Nothing? Nothing at all?

148
00:14:05,108 --> 00:14:07,110
I don't like the look of this, Fred.

149
00:14:08,695 --> 00:14:11,322
Tell you what you'd better do,
old buddy.

150
00:14:11,406 --> 00:14:13,324
You'd better give Elmo
and Charlie a blast,

151
00:14:13,408 --> 00:14:15,702
bump everything up to condition red
and stand by the blower.

152
00:14:15,785 --> 00:14:17,245
I'll get back to you.

153
00:14:17,328 --> 00:14:19,414
- What's up?
- Nothin', nothin'.

154
00:14:20,957 --> 00:14:22,542
- Where's my shorts?
- On the floor.

155
00:14:22,625 --> 00:14:24,377
Where are you going?

156
00:14:24,460 --> 00:14:26,212
No place. No place.

157
00:14:26,296 --> 00:14:29,841
I just thought I might, uh, mosey over
to the war room for a few minutes,

158
00:14:29,924 --> 00:14:31,342
see what's doing over there.

159
00:14:31,426 --> 00:14:34,679
- It's 3:00 in the morning.
- Well, the air force never sleeps.

160
00:14:34,762 --> 00:14:36,514
- Buck, honey.
- Yeah?

161
00:14:36,598 --> 00:14:38,600
I'm not sleepy either.

162
00:14:41,477 --> 00:14:43,313
I know how it is, baby.

163
00:14:44,397 --> 00:14:46,399
Tell you what you do.

164
00:14:47,358 --> 00:14:49,736
You just start your countdown,

165
00:14:49,819 --> 00:14:54,699
and old Bucky will be back here
before you can say "blast-off".

166
00:14:56,367 --> 00:14:59,621
Your commie has no regard
for human life,

167
00:14:59,704 --> 00:15:01,497
not even his own,

168
00:15:01,581 --> 00:15:04,626
and for this reason, men,
I want to impress upon you

169
00:15:04,709 --> 00:15:07,587
the need for extreme watchfulness.

170
00:15:07,670 --> 00:15:09,756
The enemy may come individually

171
00:15:09,839 --> 00:15:11,925
or he may come in strength.

172
00:15:12,008 --> 00:15:14,510
He may even come in the uniform
of our own troops.

173
00:15:15,386 --> 00:15:17,931
But however he comes,
we must stop him.

174
00:15:18,014 --> 00:15:20,975
We must not allow him
to gain entrance to this base.

175
00:15:22,352 --> 00:15:26,272
Now, I am going to give you
three simple rules.

176
00:15:26,356 --> 00:15:30,777
First, trust no one,
whatever his uniform or rank,

177
00:15:30,860 --> 00:15:33,279
unless he is known to you personally.

178
00:15:33,363 --> 00:15:34,364
Second,

179
00:15:34,447 --> 00:15:38,993
anyone or anything that approaches
within 200 yards of the perimeter

180
00:15:39,077 --> 00:15:41,287
is to be fired upon.

181
00:15:41,371 --> 00:15:42,372
Third,

182
00:15:43,289 --> 00:15:47,085
if in doubt, shoot first
and ask questions afterwards.

183
00:15:47,168 --> 00:15:50,421
I would sooner accept
a few casualties through accident

184
00:15:50,505 --> 00:15:54,634
than lose the entire base and its personnel
through carelessness.

185
00:15:54,717 --> 00:15:58,930
Any variation on these rules
must come from me personally.

186
00:15:59,931 --> 00:16:02,642
Now, men, in conclusion,

187
00:16:02,725 --> 00:16:05,103
I would like to say

188
00:16:05,186 --> 00:16:10,817
that in the two years it has been my privilege
to be your commanding officer,

189
00:16:10,900 --> 00:16:13,695
I have always expected
the best from you

190
00:16:13,778 --> 00:16:16,239
and you have never given me
anything less than that.

191
00:16:17,949 --> 00:16:20,159
Today the nation is counting on us.

192
00:16:22,370 --> 00:16:25,331
We are not going to let them down.

193
00:16:25,415 --> 00:16:27,250
Good luck to you all.

194
00:16:57,447 --> 00:16:59,824
Here's the attack profile, sir.

195
00:17:27,727 --> 00:17:30,146
This is your attack profile.

196
00:17:30,229 --> 00:17:33,316
To ensure that the enemy
cannot monitor voice transmission

197
00:17:33,399 --> 00:17:35,777
or plant false transmission,

198
00:17:35,860 --> 00:17:40,990
the CRM 114 is to be switched
into all receiver circuits.

199
00:17:41,074 --> 00:17:46,871
The emergency base code prefix
is to be set on the dials of the CRM.

200
00:17:46,954 --> 00:17:51,667
This will block any transmission other
than those preceded by a code prefix.

201
00:17:53,169 --> 00:17:55,421
Stand by to set code prefix.

202
00:17:55,505 --> 00:17:57,924
Roger. Ready to set code prefix.

203
00:17:58,007 --> 00:17:59,842
Set code prefix.

204
00:18:09,519 --> 00:18:10,812
Code prefix set.

205
00:18:10,895 --> 00:18:12,605
Lock code prefix.

206
00:18:15,358 --> 00:18:16,651
Code prefix locked.

207
00:18:16,734 --> 00:18:20,279
Switch all receiver circuits
to CRM discriminators.

208
00:18:21,906 --> 00:18:24,659
All circuits switched
to CRM discriminators.

209
00:18:24,742 --> 00:18:26,661
Check auto-destruct circuits.

210
00:18:30,039 --> 00:18:31,874
Auto-destruct circuits checked.

211
00:18:37,255 --> 00:18:41,509
Primary target,
the ICBM complex at Laputa.

212
00:18:41,592 --> 00:18:48,099
Target reference,
Yankee Golf Tango 360.

213
00:18:48,182 --> 00:18:50,143
Thirty-megaton nuclear device

214
00:18:50,226 --> 00:18:54,313
fused for airburst at 10,000 feet.

215
00:18:54,397 --> 00:18:58,693
Twenty-megaton nuclear device
will be used if first malfunctions.

216
00:18:58,776 --> 00:19:01,571
Otherwise,
proceed to secondary target,

217
00:19:01,654 --> 00:19:05,533
missile complex
seven miles east of Barchov.

218
00:19:05,616 --> 00:19:12,039
Target reference,
November Bravo X-ray, 108.

219
00:19:12,123 --> 00:19:14,959
Fused for airburst at 10.

220
00:19:15,042 --> 00:19:17,670
Check. 12,000 feet.

221
00:19:29,015 --> 00:19:30,516
Excuse me, sir.

222
00:19:30,600 --> 00:19:32,685
Something rather interesting
has just cropped up.

223
00:19:32,768 --> 00:19:36,189
Listen to that. Music.
Civilian broadcasting.

224
00:19:37,148 --> 00:19:39,275
I think those fellows in the Pentagon
have given us

225
00:19:39,358 --> 00:19:41,652
some sort of exercise
to test our readiness.

226
00:19:41,736 --> 00:19:43,905
Personally, I think
it's taking things a bit too far.

227
00:19:43,988 --> 00:19:46,699
Our fellows will be inside Russian
radar cover in about 20 minutes.

228
00:19:46,782 --> 00:19:49,493
Listen to that. Chockablock
full of stations all churning it out.

229
00:19:51,787 --> 00:19:53,622
- Mandrake?
- Yes, sir.

230
00:19:53,706 --> 00:19:56,751
I thought I issued instructions
for all radios on this base to be impounded.

231
00:19:56,834 --> 00:20:00,046
Well, you did indeed, sir, and I was
in the process of impounding this very one

232
00:20:00,129 --> 00:20:01,631
when I happened to switch it on.

233
00:20:01,714 --> 00:20:05,134
I thought, our fellows hitting Russian radar
cover in 20 minutes, dropping all their stuff,

234
00:20:05,218 --> 00:20:08,804
I'd better tell you because if they do,
it'll cause a bit of a stink, what?

235
00:20:09,639 --> 00:20:12,099
Group Captain.

236
00:20:12,183 --> 00:20:15,478
The officer exchange program does not
give you any special prerogatives

237
00:20:15,561 --> 00:20:17,396
to question my orders.

238
00:20:17,480 --> 00:20:21,651
Well, I realize that, sir, but I thought
you'd be rather pleased to hear the news.

239
00:20:21,734 --> 00:20:24,904
After all, well, let's face it,

240
00:20:24,987 --> 00:20:28,574
