10 to 20 million killed tops,

482
00:34:22,824 --> 00:34:25,160
depending on the breaks.

483
00:34:25,243 --> 00:34:29,247
I will not go down in history as the greatest
mass murderer since Adolf Hitler.

484
00:34:29,331 --> 00:34:31,249
Perhaps it might be better,
Mr. President,

485
00:34:31,333 --> 00:34:33,376
if you were more concerned
with the American people

486
00:34:33,460 --> 00:34:35,295
than with your image in the history books.

487
00:34:35,378 --> 00:34:39,674
General Turgidson, I think I've heard quite
sufficient from you, thank you very much.

488
00:34:41,176 --> 00:34:43,428
Mr. President, they have
the ambassador waiting upstairs.

489
00:34:43,512 --> 00:34:44,763
Oh, good. Any difficulty?

490
00:34:44,846 --> 00:34:47,099
They say he's having a fit
about that squad of MP's.

491
00:34:47,182 --> 00:34:49,768
Yes, well, that can't be helped.
Have him brought down here straight away.

492
00:34:49,851 --> 00:34:51,311
Yes, sir.

493
00:34:51,394 --> 00:34:53,980
Is that the Russian ambassador
you're talking about?

494
00:34:54,064 --> 00:34:56,191
Yes, it is, General.

495
00:34:58,235 --> 00:35:01,029
Am I to understand
the Russian ambassador

496
00:35:01,113 --> 00:35:03,698
is to be admitted entrance
to the war room?

497
00:35:04,199 --> 00:35:06,660
That is correct.
He is here on my orders.

498
00:35:08,203 --> 00:35:11,498
I don't know
exactly how to put this, sir,

499
00:35:11,581 --> 00:35:14,501
but are you aware of what a serious
breach of security that would be?

500
00:35:14,584 --> 00:35:19,506
I mean, he'll see everything.
He'll see the big board!

501
00:35:20,298 --> 00:35:22,634
That is precisely the idea, General.

502
00:35:22,717 --> 00:35:25,053
That is precisely the idea.

503
00:35:26,638 --> 00:35:29,891
Staines, get Premier Kissoff
on the hot line.

504
00:35:37,732 --> 00:35:40,861
Survival kit contents check.

505
00:35:41,736 --> 00:35:46,324
In them you will find one
.45 caliber automatic,

506
00:35:46,408 --> 00:35:49,119
two boxes ammunition,

507
00:35:49,202 --> 00:35:52,497
four days concentrated
emergency rations,

508
00:35:52,581 --> 00:35:55,876
one drug issue
containing antibiotics,

509
00:35:55,959 --> 00:36:00,338
morphine, vitamin pills, pep pills,

510
00:36:00,422 --> 00:36:04,176
sleeping pills, tranquilizer pills,

511
00:36:04,259 --> 00:36:09,097
one miniature combination
Russian phrase book and Bible,

512
00:36:09,181 --> 00:36:12,142
$100 in rubles,

513
00:36:12,225 --> 00:36:14,394
$100 in gold,

514
00:36:14,477 --> 00:36:19,107
nine packs of chewing gum,
one issue of prophylactics,

515
00:36:19,191 --> 00:36:23,236
three lipsticks,
three pair of nylon stockings.

516
00:36:23,320 --> 00:36:28,200
Shoot, a fella could have a pretty good
weekend in Vegas with all that stuff.

517
00:36:33,455 --> 00:36:36,541
- You don't have any fresh fish?
- I'm afraid not, sir.

518
00:36:36,625 --> 00:36:38,710
- Your eggs then. They are fresh?
- Oh, yes, sir.

519
00:36:38,793 --> 00:36:40,420
I will have poached eggs.

520
00:36:40,503 --> 00:36:42,756
And bring me some cigars, please.
Havana cigars.

521
00:36:42,839 --> 00:36:44,716
- And that will be all for you, sir?
- Yes.

522
00:36:44,799 --> 00:36:46,301
Then I'll see to it right away.

523
00:36:46,384 --> 00:36:49,554
Try one of these Jamaican cigars,
Ambassador. They're pretty good.

524
00:36:49,638 --> 00:36:53,141
Thank you, no. I do not support
the work of imperialist stooges.

525
00:36:53,225 --> 00:36:55,894
Only commie stooges, huh?

526
00:36:55,977 --> 00:36:57,562
Mr. President.

527
00:36:59,231 --> 00:37:02,859
You gonna let that lousy commie punk
vomit all over us like this?

528
00:37:02,943 --> 00:37:06,488
Mr. President, we haven't been able
to reach Premier Kissoff in the Kremlin.

529
00:37:06,571 --> 00:37:10,116
They say they don't know where he is
and he won't be back for another two hours.

530
00:37:11,284 --> 00:37:13,495
- Try B86543, Moscow.
- Yes, sir.

531
00:37:13,578 --> 00:37:15,789
You would never have found him
through his office, Mr. President.

532
00:37:15,872 --> 00:37:19,709
Our premier is a man of the people,
but he is also a man, if you follow my meaning.

533
00:37:19,793 --> 00:37:21,586
- Fine.
- Degenerate atheistic commie.

534
00:37:21,670 --> 00:37:22,921
What did you say?

535
00:37:23,004 --> 00:37:25,674
I said Premier Kissoff
is a degenerate atheistic commie!

536
00:37:25,757 --> 00:37:27,968
Mr. President, I formally request
that you have this ignorant...

537
00:37:28,051 --> 00:37:29,469
I'm sorry, Mr. President.

538
00:37:29,552 --> 00:37:32,555
Mr. President!
I think they're trying the number.

539
00:37:36,434 --> 00:37:39,604
You filthy bully! You filthy brute!

540
00:37:42,065 --> 00:37:43,984
You war-mongering bully!

541
00:37:44,067 --> 00:37:47,195
Gentlemen, you can't fight in here!
This is the war room!

542
00:37:47,279 --> 00:37:49,948
What is going on here?
I demand an explanation.

543
00:37:50,031 --> 00:37:53,785
This clumsy fool tried to plant
that ridiculous camera on me.

544
00:37:53,868 --> 00:37:56,871
Yeah, you bet your sweets, Mr. Commie.
Look at this, Mr. President.

545
00:37:56,955 --> 00:38:00,792
This lousy commie rat was taking pictures
with this thing. Of the big board!

546
00:38:01,751 --> 00:38:03,670
Mr. Ambassador!

547
00:38:03,753 --> 00:38:05,213
This clumsy fool

548
00:38:05,297 --> 00:38:07,924
attempted to plant
that ridiculous camera on me.

549
00:38:08,008 --> 00:38:10,969
That's a damn lie!
I saw him with my own eyes!

550
00:38:11,052 --> 00:38:12,512
Gentlemen, this is outrageous.

551
00:38:12,595 --> 00:38:15,265
I've never heard of such behavior
in the war room before.

552
00:38:15,348 --> 00:38:17,851
Mr. President,
I think they're getting him on the line.

553
00:38:45,754 --> 00:38:47,714
You sure gotta hand it to those commies.

554
00:38:47,797 --> 00:38:49,466
Yeah.

555
00:38:49,549 --> 00:38:52,344
Gee, those trucks sure look like
the real thing, don't they?

556
00:38:52,427 --> 00:38:54,387
I wonder where they got 'em from.

557
00:38:54,471 --> 00:38:56,723
Probably bought them from the army
as war surplus.

558
00:39:00,310 --> 00:39:04,105
Okay, open up at 200 yards.

559
00:40:01,579 --> 00:40:05,583
Tell him where you are and that you'll enter
the conversation if I say anything untrue,

560
00:40:05,667 --> 00:40:09,337
but please don't tell him
anything more than that.

561
00:40:09,421 --> 00:40:12,757
Alexi. Alexi, please, I beg you.

562
00:40:13,758 --> 00:40:16,261
I don't have a phone.

563
00:40:16,344 --> 00:40:18,346
Give him your phone, Frank.

564
00:40:45,832 --> 00:40:47,333
I've done as you asked.

565
00:40:47,417 --> 00:40:50,295
Be careful, Mr. President.
I think he is drunk.

566
00:40:53,173 --> 00:40:57,260
Hello?
Hello, D... Hello, Dmitri.

567
00:40:57,969 --> 00:40:59,762
Listen, I can't hear too well.

568
00:40:59,846 --> 00:41:03,057
Do you suppose you could
turn the music down just a little?

569
00:41:03,892 --> 00:41:05,560
Oh, that's much better.

570
00:41:05,643 --> 00:41:08,313
Yes. Yes.

571
00:41:09,397 --> 00:41:12,150
Fine. I can hear you now, Dmitri.

572
00:41:12,233 --> 00:41:15,695
Clear and plain and coming through fine.

573
00:41:15,778 --> 00:41:18,406
I'm coming through fine too, eh?
Good.

574
00:41:18,490 --> 00:41:20,283
Then...

575
00:41:20,366 --> 00:41:23,828
Well, then as you say,
we're both coming through fine.

576
00:41:23,912 --> 00:41:27,916
Good. Well, it's good
that you're fine and I'm fine.

577
00:41:28,750 --> 00:41:30,960
I agree with you.
It's great to be fine.

578
00:41:32,962 --> 00:41:35,298
Now then, Dmitri,

579
00:41:35,381 --> 00:41:37,175
you know how

580
00:41:37,258 --> 00:41:40,887
we've always talked
about the possibility

581
00:41:40,970 --> 00:41:43,723
of something going wrong
with the bomb.

582
00:41:45,016 --> 00:41:46,893
The bomb, Dmitri.

583
00:41:48,144 --> 00:41:50,188
The hydrogen bomb.

584
00:41:50,939 --> 00:41:53,816
Well, now, what happened is

585
00:41:53,900 --> 00:41:56,444
one of our base commanders,

586
00:41:56,528 --> 00:41:58,196
he had a sort of...

587
00:41:58,279 --> 00:42:01,491
Well, he went
a little funny in the head.

588
00:42:01,574 --> 00:42:04,661
You know, just a little... funny.

589
00:42:04,744 --> 00:42:08,957
And he went and did a silly thing.

590
00:42:09,707 --> 00:42:11,292
Well, I'll tell you what he did.

591
00:42:11,376 --> 00:42:13,461
He ordered his planes...

592
00:42:15,213 --> 00:42:17,340
to attack your country.

593
00:42:17,423 --> 00:42:20,426
Well, let me finish, Dmitri.

594
00:42:21,177 --> 00:42:23,388
Let me finish, Dmitri.

595
00:42:23,471 --> 00:42:26,558
Well, listen,
how do you think I feel about it?

596
00:42:26,641 --> 00:42:29,602
Can you imagine
how I feel about it, Dmitri?

597
00:42:31,229 --> 00:42:34,857
Why do you think I'm calling you?
Just to say hello?

598
00:42:36,317 --> 00:42:38,695
Of course I like to speak to you.

599
00:42:38,778 --> 00:42:41,239
Of course I like to say hello.

600
00:42:41,322 --> 00:42:43,449
Not now, but any time, Dmitri.

601
00:42:43,533 --> 00:42:47,745
I'm just calling up to tell you
something terrible has happened.

602
00:42:47,829 --> 00:42:50,790
It's a friendly call.
Of course it's a friendly call.

603
00:42:50,873 --> 00:42:55,253
Listen, if it wasn't friendly,
you probably wouldn't have even got it.

604
00:42:57,714 --> 00:43:01,593
They will not reach their targets
for at least another hour.

605
00:43:02,302 --> 00:43:05,471
I am positive, Dmitri.

606
00:43:05,555 --> 00:43:09,726
Listen, I've been all over this
with your ambassador. It is not a trick.

607
00:43:10,727 --> 00:43:12,145
Well, I'll tell you.

608
00:43:12,228 --> 00:43:15,898
We'd like to give your air staff
a complete rundown on the targets,

609
00:43:15,982 --> 00:43:19,319
the flight plans
and the defensive systems of the planes.

610
00:43:19,402 --> 00:43:23,114
Yes, I mean, if we are unable
to recall the planes,

611
00:43:23,197 --> 00:43:26,451
then I'd say that,

612
00:43:26,534 --> 00:43:31,623
well, we're just going to have to
help you destroy them, Dmitri.

613
00:43:32,957 --> 00:43:34,917
I know they're our boys.

614
00:43:35,918 --> 00:43:38,421
All right. Well, listen.
Now, who should we call?

615
00:43:40,048 --> 00:43:43,134
Who should we call, Dmitri?
The... What was... The people...

616
00:43:43,217 --> 00:43:45,219
Sorry, you faded away there.

617
00:43:45,970 --> 00:43:49,057
The People's Central Air Defense
headquarters.

618
00:43:49,891 --> 00:43:51,351
Where is that, Dmitri?

619
00:43:52,226 --> 00:43:54,103
In Omsk. Right.

620
00:43:55,480 --> 00:43:56,731
Yes.

621
00:43:56,814 --> 00:43:58,816
Oh, you'll call them first, will you?

622
00:44:01,194 --> 00:44:04,197
Listen, do you happen to have
the phone number on you, Dmitri?

623
00:44:05,073 --> 00:44:08,451
What? I see.
Just ask for Omsk information.

624
00:44:10,995 --> 00:44:13,331
I'm sorry too, Dmitri.

625
00:44:13,414 --> 00:44:15,208
I'm very sorry.

626
00:44:15,291 --> 00:44:19,170
All right, you're sorrier than I am.
But I am sorry as well.

627
00:44:21,506 --> 00:44:23,675
I am as sorry as you are, Dmitri.

628
00:44:23,758 --> 00:44:25,677
Don't say that you're
more sorry than I am,

629
00:44:25,760 --> 00:44:28,888
because I am capable of being
just as sorry as you are.

630
00:44:28,971 --> 00:44:32,266
So we're both sorry, all right?
All right.

631
00:44:33,434 --> 00:44:37,271
Yes, he's right here. Yes, he wants
to talk to you. Just a second.

632
00:44:50,993 --> 00:44:54,122
What?

633
00:45:10,388 --> 00:45:12,181
What?

634
00:45:12,265 --> 00:45:13,391
What is it? What?

635
00:45:13,474 --> 00:45:14,976
The fools.

636
00:45:15,059 --> 00:45:17,103
The mad fools.

637
00:45:17,854 --> 00:45:20,148
What's happened?

638
00:45:20,231 --> 00:45:22,650
The Doomsday Machine.

639
00:45:22,734 --> 00:45:25,278
The Doomsday Machine?
What is that?

640
00:45:25,361 --> 00:45:30,199
A device which will destroy
all human and animal life on earth.

641
00:45:30,825 --> 00:45:32,869
All human and animal life?

642
00:45:47,800 --> 00:45:49,177
Mandrake.

643
00:45:49,260 --> 00:45:51,429
Yes, Jack?

644
00:45:51,512 --> 00:45:54,515
Have you ever seen a commie
drink a glass of water?

645
00:45:55,224 --> 00:45:57,185
Well, no, I...

646
00:45:57,268 --> 00:45:59,479
I can't say I have, Jack.

647
00:46:00,897 --> 00:46:03,983
Vodka.
That's what they drink, isn't it?

648
00:46:04,066 --> 00:46:05,777
Never water.

649
00:46:05,860 --> 00:46:07,278
Well, I...

650
00:46:07,361 --> 00:46:10,239
I believe that's what
they drink, Jack, yes.

651
00:46:10,323 --> 00:46:13,785
On no account
will a commie ever drink water.

652
00:46:13,868 --> 00:46:15,870
And not without good reason.

653
00:46:17,288 --> 00:46:19,916
Oh, yes.

654
00:46:19,999 --> 00:46:23,336
I can't quite...

655
00:46:23,419 --> 00:46:26,339
see what you're getting at, Jack.

656
00:46:26,422 --> 00:46:28,508
Water.
That's what I'm getting at.

657
00:46:28,591 --> 00:46:30,051
Water.

658
00:46:31,052 --> 00:46:34,555
Mandrake,
water is the source of all life.

659
00:46:35,973 --> 00:46:38,601
Seven-tenths
of this earth's surface is water.

660
00:46:39,602 --> 00:46:41,604
Why, do you realize that...

661
00:46:43,064 --> 00:46:45,608
70% of you is water?

662
00:46:46,359 --> 00:46:47,652
Oh, how odd.

663
00:46:47,735 --> 00:46:49,487
And as human beings,

664
00:46:49,570 --> 00:46:52,698
you and I need fresh, pure water

665
00:46:52,782 --> 00:46:55,701
to replenish
our precious bodily fluids.

666
00:46:55,785 --> 00:46:57,995
- Yes.
- Are you beginning to understand?

667
00:46:58,079 --> 00:46:59,872
Yes.

668
00:47:02,750 --> 00:47:05,044
Mandrake.

669
00:47:06,671 --> 00:47:09,549
Mandrake, have you
never wondered why

670
00:47:09,632 --> 00:47:12,969
I drink only distilled water,
or rainwater,

671
00:47:13,052 --> 00:47:15,513
and only pure grain alcohol?

672
00:47:16,389 --> 00:47:19,600
Well, I... it did occur to me Jack, yes.

673
00:47:20,810 --> 00:47:23,312
Have you ever heard of a thing
called fluoridation?

674
00:47:23,396 --> 00:47:25,690
Fluoridation of water?

675
00:47:25,773 --> 00:47:28,276
Uh, yes. I have heard of that, Jack.

676
00:47:28,359 --> 00:47:29,861
Yes. Yes.

677
00:47:29,944 --> 00:47:31,612
Well, do you know what it is?

678
00:47:31,696 --> 00:47:34,824
No. No, I don't know what it is, no.

679
00:47:34,907 --> 00:47:36,868
Do you realize

680
00:47:36,951 --> 00:47:38,953
that fluoridation

681
00:47:39,036 --> 00:47:41,873
is the most monstrously conceived

682
00:47:41,956 --> 00:47:44,750
and dangerous Communist plot
we have ever had to face?

683
00:47:51,382 --> 00:47:53,134
Two can play at that game, soldier.

684
00:47:58,180 --> 00:48:00,516
That's nice shooting, soldier!

685
00:48:25,374 --> 00:48:27,501
Mandrake, come here.

686
00:48:27,585 --> 00:48:29,462
Are you calling me, Jack?

687
00:48:29,545 --> 00:48:31,923
Come over here
and help me with this belt.

688
00:48:33,382 --> 00:48:35,051
I...

689
00:48:35,134 --> 00:48:38,012
I haven't had very much experience,
you know,

690
00:48:38,095 --> 00:48:40,973
with those sort of machines, Jack.

691
00:48:41,057 --> 00:48:44,268
I've only ever pressed a button
in my old Spitfire.

692
00:48:44,352 --> 00:48:46,771
Mandrake, in the name of Her Majesty
and the Continental Congress,

693
00:48:46,854 --> 00:48:48,606
come here and feed me this belt, boy.

694
00:48:48,689 --> 00:48:52,360
Jack. I'd love to come, but

695
00:48:52,443 --> 00:48:55,905
what's happened, you see,
the string in my leg's gone.

696
00:48:57,281 --> 00:48:59,033
- The what?
- The string.

697
00:48:59,116 --> 00:49:01,243
I never told you, but you see...

698
00:49:01,327 --> 00:49:05,164
Got a gammy leg.
Oh, dear. Gone, shot off.

699
00:49:07,208 --> 00:49:10,962
Mandrake. Come over here.
The Red Coats are coming. Come on.

700
00:49:12,004 --> 00:49:16,384
When it is detonated, it will produce
enough lethal radioactive fallout

701
00:49:16,467 --> 00:49:19,595
so that within 10 months,
the surface of the Earth

702
00:49:19,679 --> 00:49:21,555
will be as dead as the moon.

703
00:49:21,639 --> 00:49:24,433
Ah, come on, de Sadesky.
That's ridiculous.

704
00:49:24,517 --> 00:49:28,646
Our studies show that even the worst fallout
is down to a safe level after two weeks.

705
00:49:28,729 --> 00:49:32,358
You've obviously never heard
of Cobalt Thorium G.

706
00:49:32,441 --> 00:49:33,943
Well, what about it?

707
00:49:34,026 --> 00:49:37,780
Cobalt Thorium G has
a radioactive half-life of 93 years.

708
00:49:37,863 --> 00:49:40,992
If you take, say, 50 H-bombs
in the hundred megaton range

709
00:49:41,075 --> 00:49:43,452
and jacket them with Cobalt Thorium G,

710
00:49:43,536 --> 00:49:48,124
when they are exploded,
they will produce a doomsday shroud,

711
00:49:48,207 --> 00:49:50,584
a lethal cloud of radioactivity

712
00:49:50,668 --> 00:49:55,047
which will encircle the Earth
for 93 years.

713
00:49:55,131 --> 00:49:57,258
Oh, what a load of commie bull.

714
00:49:57,341 --> 00:49:58,843
I mean, after all...

715
00:49:59,885 --> 00:50:02,513
I'm afraid I don't understand
something, Alexi.

716
00:50:02,596 --> 00:50:06,350
Is the premier threatening to explode this
if our planes carry out their attack?

717
00:50:06,434 --> 00:50:08,936
No, sir.
It is not a thing a sane man would do.

718
00:50:09,020 --> 00:50:11,856
The Doomsday Machine is designed
to trigger itself automatically.

719
00:50:11,939 --> 00:50:14,191
- But surely you can disarm it somehow?
- No.

720
00:50:14,275 --> 00:50:18,362
It is designed to explode if any attempt
is ever made to untrigger it.

721
00:50:18,446 --> 00:50:20,948
- Automatically?
- It's an obvious commie trick, Mr. President.

722
00:50:21,032 --> 00:50:23,576
We're wasting valuable ti...
Look at the big board.

723
00:50:23,659 --> 00:50:25,578
They're getting ready to clobber us.

724
00:50:25,661 --> 00:50:28,164
But this is absolute madness,
Ambassador.

725
00:50:28,247 --> 00:50:29,874
Why should you build such a thing?

726
00:50:29,957 --> 00:50:32,626
There were those of us
who fought against it, but in the end,

727
00:50:32,710 --> 00:50:35,379
we could not keep up with the expense
involved in the arms race,

728
00:50:35,463 --> 00:50:38,966
the space race and the peace race.

729
00:50:39,050 --> 00:50:44,221
And at the same time, our people grumbled
for more nylons and washing machines.

730
00:50:44,305 --> 00:50:47,641
Our doomsday scheme cost us just a small
fraction of what we'd been spending

731
00:50:47,725 --> 00:50:50,061
on defense in a single year.

732
00:50:50,144 --> 00:50:52,813
But the deciding factor
was when we learned that your country

733
00:50:52,897 --> 00:50:54,690
was working along similar lines

734
00:50:54,774 --> 00:50:56,859
and we were afraid
of a doomsday gap.

735
00:50:56,942 --> 00:51:00,154
This is preposterous.
I've never approved of anything like that.

736
00:51:00,237 --> 00:51:03,115
Our source was The New York Times.

737
00:51:03,866 --> 00:51:07,078
Dr. Strangelove, do we have
anything like that in the works?

738
00:51:07,161 --> 00:51:09,371
A moment, please, Mr. President.

739
00:51:12,333 --> 00:51:15,628
Under the authority granted me

740
00:51:15,711 --> 00:51:19,840
as director of weapons research
and development,

741
00:51:19,924 --> 00:51:24,136
I commissioned last year
a study of this project

742
00:51:24,220 --> 00:51:26,597
by the Bland Corporation.

743
00:51:26,680 --> 00:51:29,725
Based on the findings of the report,

744
00:51:29,809 --> 00:51:35,231
my conclusion was that this idea
was not a practical deterrent

745
00:51:35,314 --> 00:51:39,276
for reasons which, at this moment,
must be all too obvious.

746
00:51:39,360 --> 00:51:42,780
Then you mean it is possible
for them to have built such a thing?

747
00:51:46,784 --> 00:51:49,829
Mr. President,
the technology required

748
00:51:49,912 --> 00:51:56,168
is easily within the means
of even the smallest nuclear power.

749
00:51:56,252 --> 00:52:00,422
It requires only the will to do so.

750
00:52:01,298 --> 00:52:05,052
But how is it possible for this thing
to be triggered automatically

751
00:52:05,136 --> 00:52:07,555
and at the same time,
impossible to untrigger?

752
00:52:07,638 --> 00:52:11,809
Mr. President,
it is not only possible,

753
00:52:11,892 --> 00:52:13,519
it is essential.

754
00:52:13,602 --> 00:52:18,065
That is the whole idea
of this machine, you know.

755
00:52:18,149 --> 00:52:23,362
Deterrence is the art of producing
in the mind of the enemy

756
00:52:23,445 --> 00:52:26,157
the fear to attack.

757
00:52:26,240 --> 00:52:31,036
And so, because of the automated
and irrevocable decision-making process

758
00:52:31,120 --> 00:52:34,999
which rules out human meddling,

759
00:52:35,082 --> 00:52:39,044
the Doomsday Machine is terrifying.

760
00:52:39,128 --> 00:52:41,338
Yes, and simple to understand.

761
00:52:41,422 --> 00:52:44,884
And completely credible and convincing.

762
00:52:44,967 --> 00:52:47,970
I wish we had one of them
Doomsday Machines, Stainsey.

763
00:52:48,053 --> 00:52:50,139
But this is fantastic, Strangelove.

764
00:52:50,222 --> 00:52:52,183
How can it be triggered automatically?

765
00:52:52,266 --> 00:52:55,895
Well, it's remarkably simple to do that.

766
00:52:55,978 --> 00:52:59,481
When you merely wish to bury bombs,

767
00:52:59,565 --> 00:53:01,984
there's no limit to the size.

768
00:53:02,067 --> 00:53:04,278
After that, they are connected

769
00:53:04,361 --> 00:53:08,324
to a gigantic complex of computers.

770
00:53:08,407 --> 00:53:14,246
Now then, a specific and clearly defined
set of circumstances

771
00:53:14,330 --> 00:53:17,708
under which the bombs
are to be exploded

772
00:53:17,791 --> 00:53:21,879
is programmed
into a tape memory bank.

773
00:53:21,962 --> 00:53:24,506
- Strangelove.
- A single roll of tape

774
00:53:24,590 --> 00:53:27,468
- can store all the information...
- What kind of a name is that?

775
00:53:27,551 --> 00:53:29,261
That ain't no Kraut name,
is it, Stainsey?

776
00:53:29,345 --> 00:53:31,555
He changed it
when he became a citizen.

777
00:53:31,639 --> 00:53:33,599
It used to be Merkwurdichliebe.

778
00:53:34,600 --> 00:53:39,104
Well, a Kraut by any other name,
Stainsey?

779
00:53:40,898 --> 00:53:45,236
...is that the whole point
of the Doomsday Machine

780
00:53:45,319 --> 00:53:48,697
is lost if you keep it a secret.

781
00:53:48,781 --> 00:53:51,242
Why didn't you tell the world, eh?

782
00:53:51,325 --> 00:53:55,704
It was to be announced
at the Party Congress on Monday.

783
00:53:55,788 --> 00:53:59,083
As you know,
the premier loves surprises.

784
00:54:47,589 --> 00:54:49,591
Stay with me, Mandrake.

785
00:54:54,722 --> 00:54:57,558
All right, Mandrake.
Now feed me, feed me, boy.

786
00:55:27,588 --> 00:55:30,388
Jack, don't you think we'd be better off
in some other part of the room

787
00:55:30,466 --> 00:55:32,384
